An IoT gateway is a device that acts as an intermediary between IoT sensor nodes and the cloud.
It collects data from multiple sensors, processes or filters the data if needed, converts communication protocols,
and securely forwards the information to cloud servers.
The gateway also receives commands from the cloud and sends them back to the appropriate IoT devices.
This improves security, reduces network traffic, and enables communication between devices using different protocols.
+----------------+      +----------------+      +----------------+      +------------------+
| IoT Sensor     | ---> | IoT Gateway    | ---> | Cloud Platform | ---> | User Application |
| Nodes          |      | (ESP32/RPi)    |      | (AWS/Blynk)    |      | (Mobile/Web App) |
+----------------+      +----------------+      +----------------+      +------------------+
| Layer                          | Typical Protocols                      |
| ------------------------------ | -------------------------------------- |
| **IoT Sensor Nodes → Gateway** | Wi-Fi, Bluetooth, Zigbee, LoRa, Z-Wave |
| **Gateway → Cloud**            | MQTT, HTTPS/HTTP, CoAP                 |
| **Cloud → User Application**   | HTTPS, MQTT, WebSocket, REST API       |
Explanation
Sensor Nodes: Collect data such as temperature, humidity, or motion.
Gateway: Aggregates data, performs protocol conversion, and securely forwards it to the cloud.
Cloud: Stores, analyzes, and processes the data.
User Application: Displays real-time information and allows users to monitor or control IoT devices remotely.

Examples of IoT Gateways: ESP32, Raspberry Pi, industrial IoT gateways, or dedicated edge computing devices.
